{"key":"post-10412460","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10412460</id>\n<content>If you stand a cylinder on end, the water will drain by gravity to the other end and the top will dry out.&amp;nbsp; That's why I found you get much better performance from straw logs when they're laying down.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Also, there's no law that says a rectangle substrate can only fruit from one of its six sides.&amp;nbsp; You can easily pop them out of the pan and stand on edge.&amp;nbsp; A few growers have done this and had pretty amazing results.&amp;nbsp; Moisture control becomes labor intensive, but if you're experimenting, go for it.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>10412490</next>\n<prev>10412390</prev>\n<first>10412112</first>\n<last>10412533</last>\n<when>1243521922</when>\n<utime>05/28/09 05:45 PM</utime>\n</post>"}